{/* Use standard container and spacing */}
<div class="container mx-auto px-4 py-12 md:py-16 space-y-12 md:space-y-16">

  {/* Module Header */}
  <header class="text-center max-w-3xl mx-auto space-y-4">
    <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-serif font-semibold text-gray-900">
      {Astro.props.title}
    </h1>
    <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-gray-600">
      {Astro.props.description}
    </p>
  </header>

  {/* Introduction Section */}
  <section class="bg-white p-6 md:p-8 rounded-lg shadow-sm border border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-6">Introduction</h2>
    <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-gray-600 space-y-4">
      <p>
        The 7 Element Framework, developed by the Harvard Negotiation Project, provides a comprehensive approach to negotiation preparation and execution. This systematic framework helps negotiators analyze, prepare for, and conduct more effective negotiations by focusing on seven key elements.
      </p>
      <p>
        In this module, you'll learn how to apply each element to your negotiations, from identifying underlying interests to crafting clear commitments. You'll develop practical skills for using this framework to prepare for negotiations and navigate them successfully.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-8 pt-6 border-t border-gray-200">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-serif font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-4">Learning Objectives</h3>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-600">
        <li>Understand and apply the 7 Element Framework to negotiation preparation</li>
        <li>Distinguish between positions and interests in negotiation contexts</li>
        <li>Develop and evaluate alternatives (BATNA) to strengthen your negotiation position</li>
        <li>Generate creative options that satisfy multiple parties' interests</li>
        <li>Identify and apply objective criteria to support your proposals</li>
        <li>Improve communication effectiveness during negotiations</li>
        <li>Manage relationships while addressing substantive issues</li>
        <li>Create clear, realistic, and operational commitments</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* Module Content Section */}
  <section class="space-y-8">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-serif font-semibold text-gray-900 text-center mb-10">Overview of the 7 Element Framework</h2>

    {/* Overview Card */}
    <div class="bg-white p-6 md:p-8 rounded-lg shadow-sm border border-gray-200">
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-gray-600 mb-8">
        <p>
          The 7 Element Framework provides a structured approach to negotiation that helps you prepare thoroughly and navigate complex discussions effectively. Each element addresses a critical aspect of negotiation:
        </p>
      </div>

      {/* Framework Diagram Replacement (Grid) */}
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6 mb-8">
        {[
          { num: 1, title: 'Interests', desc: 'The underlying needs, desires, concerns, and fears' },
          { num: 2, title: 'Alternatives (BATNA)', desc: 'What parties can do if they fail to reach agreement' },
          { num: 3, title: 'Relationships', desc: 'The connection between parties and how it affects the process' },
          { num: 4, title: 'Options', desc: 'Possible agreements or parts of agreements' },
          { num: 5, title: 'Legitimacy', desc: 'Objective standards that justify fairness' },
          { num: 6, title: 'Communication', desc: 'The exchange of information and perspectives' },
          { num: 7, title: 'Commitments', desc: 'Agreements, promises, and obligations made' },
        ].map(item => (
          <div class="bg-gray-50 p-4 rounded-md border border-gray-200">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-serif font-semibold text-purple-700 mb-2">{item.num}. {item.title}</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">{item.desc}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-gray-600">
        <p>
          By addressing each element systematically, you can approach negotiations with greater confidence, flexibility, and effectiveness.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-serif font-semibold text-gray-900 text-center pt-8 mb-10">The 7 Elements in Detail</h2>

    {/* Element Detail Cards */}
    {[
      { title: 'Interests', content: `<p>Interests are the underlying needs, desires, concerns, and fears... They differ from positions...</p><h4>Positions vs. Interests</h4><div class="overflow-x-auto"><table class="simple-table"><thead><tr><th>Positions</th><th>Interests</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>What someone says they want</td><td>Why they want it</td></tr><tr><td>Specific solutions</td><td>Underlying motivations</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h4>Key Points:</h4><ul class="key-points"><li>Multiple interests usually exist</li><li>Can include substantive, procedural, relationship</li><li>Understanding both sides is crucial</li></ul><div class="example-box"><h4>Example:</h4><p><strong>Position:</strong> "I want three days off."</p><p><strong>Possible Interests:</strong> Family vacation, medical needs, burnout.</p></div>` },
      { title: 'Alternatives (BATNA)', content: `<p>Alternatives represent what parties can do if they fail to reach an agreement. The Best Alternative To a Negotiated Agreement (BATNA)...</p><h4>Key Points:</h4><ul class="key-points"><li>BATNA determines power</li><li>Improving BATNA strengthens position</li><li>Never accept less than BATNA</li></ul><div class="example-box"><h4>Example:</h4><p>Buying a car BATNA: Offer from another dealer, different model, wait for new releases.</p></div>` },
      { title: 'Relationships', content: `<p>The relationship between negotiating parties affects both the process and outcomes...</p><h4>Key Points:</h4><ul class="key-points"><li>Consider relationship importance (one-time vs. ongoing)</li><li>Separate relationship from substance</li><li>Build rapport and trust</li></ul><div class="example-box"><h4>Example:</h4><p>Negotiating with long-term supplier: Pushing too hard damages relationship, affecting future service/flexibility.</p></div>` },
      { title: 'Options', content: `<p>Options are the possible agreements or parts of agreements that could satisfy interests...</p><h4>Key Points:</h4><ul class="key-points"><li>Options differ from alternatives</li><li>Brainstorm before evaluating</li><li>Create value through trades</li></ul><div class="example-box"><h4>Example:</h4><p>Car purchase options: Financing, warranties, accessories, delivery timing.</p></div>` },
      { title: 'Legitimacy', content: `<p>Legitimacy refers to objective standards, criteria, or benchmarks that justify fairness...</p><h4>Key Points:</h4><ul class="key-points"><li>External standards provide objective validation</li><li>Includes market value, precedent, law, norms</li><li>Strengthens position</li></ul><div class="example-box"><h4>Example:</h4><p>Salary negotiation standards: Industry surveys, company pay scales, cost-of-living data.</p></div>` },
      { title: 'Communication', content: `<p>Effective communication is essential throughout the negotiation process...</p><h4>Key Points:</h4><ul class="key-points"><li>Active listening is key</li><li>Ask open-ended questions</li><li>Acknowledge understanding</li></ul><div class="example-box"><h4>Example:</h4><p>Instead of "Deadline impossible," ask "What factors drive timeline?" Use paraphrasing: "So your main concern is..."</p></div>` },
      { title: 'Commitments', content: `<p>Commitments are the agreements, promises, and obligations parties make...</p><h4>Key Points:</h4><ul class="key-points"><li>Well-crafted commitments are clear, realistic, operational</li><li>Consider timing</li><li>Include monitoring</li></ul><div class="example-box"><h4>Example:</h4><p>Strong commitment: "Deliver status report by 15th monthly..." vs. Weak: "Provide regular updates."</p></div>` },
    ].map((item, index) => (
      <div class="bg-white p-6 md:p-8 rounded-lg shadow-sm border border-gray-200">
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-4">{index + 1}. {item.title}</h3>
        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-gray-600 space-y-4" set:html={item.content}>
          {/* Content is injected here */}
        </div>
        {/* Application Tips (Example for one card, repeat/adapt as needed) */}
        { index === 0 && <div class="mt-6 pt-4 border-t border-gray-200"><h4>Application Tips:</h4><ul class="key-points"><li>Prepare by listing interests</li><li>Anticipate counterpart's interests</li><li>Use open-ended questions</li></ul></div>}
      </div>
    ))}

    {/* Applying the Framework Card */}
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-serif font-semibold text-gray-900 text-center pt-8 mb-10">Applying the Framework</h2>
    <div class="bg-white p-6 md:p-8 rounded-lg shadow-sm border border-gray-200">
       <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-gray-600 mb-6">
           <p>
             The real power of the 7 Element Framework comes from using it as both a preparation tool and a diagnostic tool during negotiations.
           </p>
       </div>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
            <div>
                <h3 class="text-xl font-serif font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-4">Preparation Guidelines</h3>
                <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-600">
                  <li>Create a preparation document for each element</li>
                  <li>Analyze your side, then counterpart's perspective</li>
                  <li>Identify challenges and opportunities</li>
                  <li>Develop strategies</li>
                  <li>Prioritize elements</li>
                </ol>
            </div>
             <div>
                <h3 class="text-xl font-serif font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-4">Diagnostic Use During Negotiation</h3>
                 <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">When negotiations become difficult, diagnose the source:</p>
                 <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-gray-600 text-sm">
                   <li>Failing to understand interests?</li>
                   <li>BATNA imbalance?</li>
                   <li>Relationship tensions interfering?</li>
                   <li>Not enough options generated?</li>
                   <li>Disagreeing on legitimacy?</li>
                   <li>Poor communication?</li>
                   <li>Unclear commitments?</li>
                 </ul>
             </div>
        </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* Conclusion Section */}
  <section class="bg-white p-6 md:p-8 rounded-lg shadow-sm border border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-6">Conclusion</h2>
     <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-gray-600 space-y-4">
       <p>
         Harvard's 7 Element Framework provides a powerful structure for approaching negotiations systematically. By understanding and addressing interests, alternatives, relationships, options, legitimacy, communication, and commitments, you can navigate complex negotiations more effectively.
       </p>
       <p>
         Remember that the elements are interconnected—progress in one area often creates momentum in others. With practice, this framework will become a natural part of your negotiation thinking, helping you achieve better outcomes while maintaining important relationships.
       </p>
     </div>

     <div class="mt-8 pt-6 border-t border-gray-200">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-serif font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-4">Next Steps</h3>
         <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">
            In the next module, we'll explore specific negotiation tactics and how to respond to them effectively. You'll learn to recognize common tactics, understand their purpose, and develop appropriate responses that keep negotiations productive and principled.
         </p>
